  "prompt": "How do you factory reset an iPhone 4 without a computer?",
  "response": "You can't perform a full factory reset (erase all content and settings) on an iPhone 4 **without** using a computer if you can't access the settings menu. However, if you *can* access the settings menu, here's how to factory reset:\n\n**If you can access the Settings menu:**\n\n1.  **Back up your iPhone (Recommended):**  This is crucial. A factory reset will erase everything. Back up using iCloud (if you have enough storage) or a computer if possible (though you stated you don't want to use a computer).\n2.  **Go to Settings:** Tap the Settings app icon.\n3.  **Tap General:** Scroll down and tap on the \"General\" option.\n4.  **Scroll Down and Tap Reset:** Scroll to the bottom of the General screen and tap \"Reset\".\n5.  **Tap Erase All Content and Settings:** Tap on the \"Erase All Content and Settings\" option.\n6.  **Enter Passcode (if applicable):** If you have a passcode enabled, you'll be prompted to enter it.\n7.  **Confirm Erase:** You'll likely see a warning message confirming that you want to erase everything. Tap \"Erase\" (or \"Erase iPhone\") to confirm.\n8.  **Apple ID Password (if applicable):**  You may be asked to enter your Apple ID password to disable Activation Lock. This is important, or the phone will remain locked to your Apple ID.\n9.  **Wait for the Reset:** The iPhone will begin erasing all data and settings. This process can take several minutes.  Do not interrupt the process.\n10. **iPhone Restarts:** Once the reset is complete, the iPhone will restart and you'll see the \"Hello\" setup screen, just like when it was brand new.\n\n**Important Considerations and Limitations:**\n\n*   **Activation Lock:**  Make absolutely sure you know the Apple ID and password associated with the iPhone. If you don't, and you perform a reset, the phone will be Activation Locked, and you won't be able to use it.  There is *no way* to bypass Activation Lock without the correct credentials.\n*   **Damaged Screen/Buttons:** If you have a broken screen or non-functional buttons that prevent you from navigating the Settings menu, you will *not* be able to factory reset without using a computer (recovery mode restore via iTunes).\n*   **No Settings Access:**  If you cannot access the settings menu due to a software glitch, forgotten passcode, or other problem, a factory reset without a computer is impossible.\n\n**In summary, a full factory reset without using a computer is only possible if you can navigate to and use the \"Erase All Content and Settings\" option within the iPhone's Settings app and you know the Apple ID and password.**\n\nIf you cannot access the settings menu, you are out of luck without access to a computer to perform a recovery mode restore via iTunes. Since you specifically asked for a method without a computer, I cannot provide you with a solution.\n",
